TY  - JOUR
T1  - Does Perceived Organizational Support Mediate the Relationship between Procedural Justice and Organizational Citizenship Behavior?
AU  - Moorman, Robert H.
AU  - Blakely, Gerald L.
AU  - Niehoff, Brian P.
Y1  - 1998/06/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256913
DO  - 10.5465/256913
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 351
EP  - 357
VL  - 41
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Our purpose was to test an explanation of how procedural justice may influence organizational citizenship behavior (OCB). The model tested suggests that procedural justice affects OCB by influencing perceived organizational support, which in turn prompts employees to reciprocate with organizational citizenship behaviors. Results suggest that procedural justice is an antecedent to perceived organizational support, which in turn fully mediates its relationship to three of four OCB dimensions.
AB  - Our purpose was to test an explanation of how procedural justice may influence organizational citizenship behavior (OCB). The model tested suggests that procedural justice affects OCB by influencing perceived organizational support, which in turn prompts employees to reciprocate with organizational citizenship behaviors. Results suggest that procedural justice is an antecedent to perceived organizational support, which in turn fully mediates its relationship to three of four OCB dimensions.
