TY  - JOUR
T1  - Political-Economic Context and Sensitivity to Equity: Differences between the United States and the Transition Economies of Central and Eastern Europe
AU  - Mueller, Stephen L.
AU  - Clarke, Linda D.
Y1  - 1998/06/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256910
DO  - 10.5465/256910
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 319
EP  - 329
VL  - 41
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Recent labor economics studies suggest that low enterprise productivity in former socialist economies can be corrected by adopting reward systems emphasizing compensation for performance. We used the equity sensitivity construct to test for differences in the attitudes toward equity of business students from the United States and five countries of Central and Eastern Europe. ?Entitlement attitudes? were more pervasive in the transition economies of Central and Eastern Europe than in the United States, suggesting U.S. compensation practices may not be directly applicable in that region.
AB  - Recent labor economics studies suggest that low enterprise productivity in former socialist economies can be corrected by adopting reward systems emphasizing compensation for performance. We used the equity sensitivity construct to test for differences in the attitudes toward equity of business students from the United States and five countries of Central and Eastern Europe. ?Entitlement attitudes? were more pervasive in the transition economies of Central and Eastern Europe than in the United States, suggesting U.S. compensation practices may not be directly applicable in that region.
